<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Tue Sep  2  6:53:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Since coming on line a year or so ago, I have come to the realization that many who have the most anger concerning the war are those who had a greater stake in it personally - the volunteers. I was drafted. I had the convenience of taking part without being required to have an opinion.<br><br>
Maybe that is why I was able to adjust a bit easier when I came home. I never considered myself a loser as far as not being on the victorious side. I always have considered my self as one who was fortunate enough to survive. <br><br>
I participated in a war in which I killed - not knowing why. That can be a tragedy in itself. To kill without considering the other person your enemy. The dehumanizing process never fully worked for me.<br><br>
At that time in my life, I was unable to understand the politics. However, I still could witness the world's greatest power laying waste to an impoverished country and its people.<br><br>
The continual reference to &quot;gooks&quot; is like someone trumpeting a sour note. Some attempt to justify the use of the word, showing their audaciousness by repeating it over and over. They defend and play the continual careless, sour notes -stubbornly. Jazz. <br><br>
I loved and admired the Vietnamese people. The constant pain  - that my visit to their country has caused me - does nothing to further my capacity to understand *their* suffering. Precious little is spoken of their torment.<br><br>
Which leads me to say to those who protested our involvement that I can not blame you for refusing to take part in the war. <br><br>
Glory belongs to God. To openly seek glory is to edify oneself. Those who profess their Christianity on this site should know that the proper course is to reach out, yes, to turn the other cheek even. <br><br>
My loading dead Americans onto helicopters is not cause enough for me to be a proponent of the war which I hated. I grieve for my lost friends on a daily basis. Speaking out against a war which robbed them and their families is not, in my opinion, a show of disrespect or disregard. Rather it is to insure those who will see glory in the next adventure - the next Vietnam - that there are some out there who will take issue and ask, &quot;Why and what for&quot;?<br>
 
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


